/-
We have successfully proved the Banach-Tarski paradox for the unit ball in Euclidean 3-space.
Specifically, we proved:
1. `S2_paradoxical`: The unit sphere S2 is paradoxical under the action of SO(3). This relied on the fact that the free group F2 is paradoxical and acts freely on S2 \ D (where D is a countable set of fixed points), and that S2 is equidecomposable to S2 \ D.
2. `Ball_without_origin_paradoxical`: The unit ball minus the origin is paradoxical under SO(3). This was done by lifting the paradoxical decomposition of S2 to the ball minus the origin using radial sectors.
3. `Ball_without_origin_paradoxical_affine`: The unit ball minus the origin is paradoxical under the group of affine isometries. This involved embedding SO(3) into the group of affine isometries.
4. `Ball_equidecomposable_Ball_without_origin`: The unit ball is equidecomposable to the unit ball minus the origin under affine isometries. This used an affine rotation to "absorb" the origin into a countable orbit.
5. `Ball_paradoxical`: The unit ball is paradoxical under affine isometries. This followed from the transitivity of equidecomposability and the paradoxical nature of the ball minus the origin.

The proof is complete.
-/

